   854→## 19. WATER/LAGOON RENDERING RULES
   855→
   856→### Truth-Based Visualization Only
   857→
   858→**Water between node clusters appears ONLY when it represents real data:**
   859→
   860→#### When Water IS Meaningful:
   861→```css
   862→/* Sparse connection regions - actual low connectivity */
   863→.cluster-gap {
   864→  background: linear-gradient(135deg, #87CEEB, #4682B4);
   865→  opacity: 0.3;
   866→}
   867→```
   868→
   869→**Meaning:** The "water" between islands represents genuine sparsity in the graph. Few or no direct connections between these clusters. Navigation requires crossing open water (longer cognitive traversal).
   870→
   871→#### When Water Shows Activity:
   872→```css
   873→/* Subentity traversing between clusters */
   874→@keyframes waterCrossing {
   875→  0% { opacity: 0.3; }
   876→  50% { opacity: 0.5; }  /* Ripples when subentity crosses */
   877→  100% { opacity: 0.3; }
   878→}
   879→```
   880→
   881→**Meaning:** Ripple animation ONLY appears when an subentity actually traverses between distant clusters. The water responds to real traversal activity.
   882→
   883→#### What We DON'T Do:
   884→❌ Ambient wave animations "for atmosphere"  
   885→❌ Decorative ripples without traversal  
   886→❌ Particle effects in water just because it looks cool  
   887→❌ Animated reflections that don't show real light sources  
   888→
   889→**Philosophy:** If the water doesn't represent actual graph sparsity or actual traversal activity, it doesn't animate.
